quran[13]{c,v,t,f}:
  19,52,"And We called out to him from the right side of Mount Tûr, and brought him near in communion."
  19,53,"And We granted him, of Our mercy, his brother Aaron as a prophet."
  19,54,"And mention in the Scripture Ishmael; he was indeed true to his promise, and he was a messenger<i class=""s"">(and) </i>a prophet."
  19,55,"And he used to command his family to prayer and purifying charity{1}, and with his Lord he was always rendered pleased.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is zakāt, which denotes purification and growth.
  19,56,"And mention in the Scripture Enoch; he was indeed an unwavering believer<i class=""s"">(and) </i>a prophet."
  19,57,"And We raised him to a high position."
  19,58,"Those are the ones whom Allah{1}blessed ofthe prophets from the offspring of Adam, and from those We{2}carried with Noah, and from the offspring of Abraham and Israel, and from those We guided and selected. Whenever the signs{3}of the All-Merciful<a class=""sup""><sup>b </sup></a>were recited to them, they would fall down prostrating and weeping.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 1st person to 3rd person.A grammatical shift from 3rd person to 1st person.The Arabic word used isayat(singularayah). Ayahmeans ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an,like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose.Each such unit isconsidered a ‘sign’from God.
  19,59,"Then they were succeeded by generations who wasted the prayers and followed desires, and thus they will encounter<i class=""s"">(the sequel of their) </i>delusion—"
  19,60,"except for whoever repented and believed and acted righteously, for those <span class=""h"">shall enter<sup foot_note=""80521"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>the Garden and shall not be dealt with unjustly in any way—"
  19,61,"the Gardens of Eden which have been promised by the All-Merciful to His servants in the hidden realm; indeed, His promise has ever been coming true."
  19,62,"Therein they hear no idle talk, but only peace. And therein they have their own provision, morning and evening."
  19,63,"Such is the Garden<i class=""s"">(of Paradise) </i>which We give as inheritance to whoever of Our servants who has been mindful<i class=""s"">(of God) </i>."
  19,64,"“And we{1}do not descend except by the command of your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord; to Him belongs whatever is before us and whatever is behind us and whatever is between them, and your Lord has never been forgetful.”",footnotes:1:Gabriel speaks about himself and about the angels.
